</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="118" pageNumber="397" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="118.[2057,2657,931,1353]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">
Populations in Sierra Mazateca, 
<taxonomicName box="[2542,2648,1053,1078]" class="Insecta" family="Acrididae" genus="Oaxaca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="118" pageNumber="397" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Oaxaca</taxonomicName>
, just described as a different species H. villai Leon-Paniagua, Guevara &amp; Navarro-Sigtienza, 2017. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="118" pageNumber="397" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6761115" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6761115" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6761115/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="397" startId="118.[2063,2235,1203,1236]" targetBox="[1448,2039,937,1352]" targetPageId="118">
<paragraph blockId="118.[2057,2657,931,1353]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2063,2239,1203,1236]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">Distribution.</emphasis>
E slopes oFSierra Madre Oriental in Hidalgo and Veracruz, Mexico.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="118" pageNumber="397" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="118.[2057,2657,931,1353]" lastBlockId="118.[1449,2657,1369,1985]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2063,2313,1281,1314]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 90-92 mm, tail 78-111 mm, ear 16-19 mm, hindfoot 21-24 mm; weight 17-19 g. The Xico Deermouse is a medium-sized species of 
<taxonomicName class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Habromys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="118" pageNumber="397" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Habromys</taxonomicName>
, with dark brown dorsum and white belly. Feet are small and have well-marked spots on metatarsal region; ears are medium-sized and dark; and tail is unicolored or with thin white line below and hairy and brushytip.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="118" pageNumber="397" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="118.[1449,2657,1369,1985]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1450,1562,1518,1551]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">Habitat.</emphasis>
Old and humid cloud forests with dense vegetation and mixed forests of pineoak at elevations of 1830-2200 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1451,2371,1601,1630]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="118.[1449,2657,1369,1985]" box="[1451,2371,1601,1630]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1451,1712,1601,1630]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
The Xico Deermouse is probably omnivorous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1451,1824,1640,1669]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="118.[1449,2657,1369,1985]" box="[1451,1824,1640,1669]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1451,1585,1640,1669]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">Breeding.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="118" pageNumber="397" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="118.[1449,2657,1369,1985]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1449,1687,1676,1709]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Xico Deermice are nocturnal and arboreal; they have been caught in trees up to 10-12 m high.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1451,2390,1754,1787]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="118.[1449,2657,1369,1985]" box="[1451,2390,1754,1787]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1451,2151,1754,1787]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="118" pageNumber="397" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="118.[1449,2657,1369,1985]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1451,1801,1798,1827]" pageId="118" pageNumber="397">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Endangered on The IUCN Red List. Distribution is severely fragmented, and extent and quality of its habitat continue to decline.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
